      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(security): make safeEqualSecret timing-safe for empty/null inputs",
        "body": "### Summary\r\n\r\nFixes a timing side-channel vulnerability in `safeEqualSecret` when handling `null`, `undefined`, or empty string inputs (UG #10).\r\n\r\n### Problem\r\n\r\nThe original implementation returned early if inputs were not of type `string`. This \"fast-fail\" path is significantly faster than the hashing path. This timing difference could allow an attacker to infer whether the stored secret is empty or invalid via timing attacks.\r\n\r\n### Solution\r\n\r\n1. **Removed Early Return**: Deleted the `typeof provided !== \"string\"` check that caused the timing discrepancy.\r\n2. **Input Normalization**: `null` and `undefined` inputs are now normalized to an empty string `\"\"`.\r\n3. **Constant-Time Comparison**: The function now always computes the SHA-256 hash and uses `timingSafeEqual`, ensuring the execution time is independent of the input validity.\r\n4. **Result Validation**: The final result checks the original types, ensuring the function returns `true` only if both inputs are valid strings and their digests match.\r\n\r\n### Changes\r\n\r\n- `src/security/secret-equal.ts`: Refactored `safeEqualSecret` to ensure constant-time execution for all input types.\r\n\r\n### Impact\r\n\r\n- Fixes a potential security vulnerability (information leakage via timing).\r\n- No breaking changes; function signature and external behavior remain correct.\r\n\r\n### Testing\r\n\r\n- `pnpm build`: Passed.\r\n- `pnpm check`: Passed.\r\n\r\nRefs: UG #10\r\n",
